efn|name=Jeon So-min Fatigue}}\n| April 26, 2020<br />{{small|(April 13, 2020)}}\n| ''Episode 500: Greedy Camping Race - Do you eat and run?''\n{{Lang|ko|(500\ud68c: \uc695\uc2ec\uc7c1\uc774 \ucea0\ud551 \ub808\uc774\uc2a4\uff0d\ubc25\uc740 \uba39\uace0 \ub2ec\ub9ac\ub0d0?)}}\n| {{CGuest|[[Choi Yoo-jung (singer)|Choi Yoo-jung]] ([[Weki Meki]])<br />[[Chungha]]<br />[[Lee Mi-joo]] ([[Lovelyz]])<br />[[Park Cho-rong]]<br />[[Yoon Bo-mi]] ([[Apink]])}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| Human Team<br />{{small|()}}\n| Greedy Ghost<br />{{small|()}}\n| {{TBA}}\n|-\n!501{{efn|name=Jeon So-min Fatigue}}\n| May 3, 2020<br />{{small|(April 20, 2020)}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n|-\n!502\n| May 10, 2020<br />{{small|(April 27, 2020)}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|ko}} [http://tv.sbs.co.kr/newsunday ''Running Man''] on the Official ''[[Good Sunday]]'' page\n* {{in lang|ko}} [http://runningman.sbs.co.kr/ ''Running Man'' Official Homepage] on [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] ''The Soty''\n\n{{Running Man}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Running Man'' episodes (2020)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Running Man (TV Series)}}\n[[Category:Lists of Running Man episodes]]\n[[Category:Lists of variety television series episodes]]\n[[Category:Lists of South Korean television series episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 in South Korean television]]\n", "name_user": "Jasonb28", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUpcoming episodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Running_Man_episodes_(2020)"}
{"title_page": "List of captive killer whales", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Expand list|date=July 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n\n[[File:0703 SD Breaching02.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Orca show at [[SeaWorld San Diego]].]]\n\nThis article gives a '''list of captive orcas, large predatory [[cetacean]]s that were first captured live and displayed in exhibitions in the 1960s, or were subsequently born in zoological facilities. They soon became popular attractions at [[public aquarium]]s and aquatic theme parks due to their intelligence, trainability, striking appearance, playfulness in captivity and sheer size.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdcs.org/dan/publishing.nsf/allweb/A141A8A02A2FE3C7802568F60029D1F9 |title=Orcas in captivity |publisher=Whale and Dolphin Conservation Society |accessdate=July 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070805220554/http://www.wdcs.org/dan/publishing.nsf/allweb/A141A8A02A2FE3C7802568F60029D1F9 |archivedate=August 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> As of February 2019,  captive orcas reside at facilities in North and South America, Europe and Asia.\n\nThe first North Eastern Pacific orca, Wanda,was captured in November 1961 by a collecting crew from [[Marineland of the Pacific]], and over the next 15 years, around 60 or 70 orcas were taken from Pacific waters for this purpose.<ref name=\"Heimlich\">Heimlich, Sara and Boran, James. ''Killer Whales'' (2001) Voyageur Press, Stillwater, Minnesota.</ref>\nWhen the [[Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972|US Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972]] effectively stopped the capture of Pacific orcas, captures were made in Icelandic waters.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/whales/keiko/world.html \"A Whale of a Business\"] PBS, Reproduced from \"The Performing Orca, Why the Show Must Stop\" by Erich Hoyt. Retrieved February 14, 2009.</ref> Since 2010, captures have been made in Russian waters. However, facilities in the United States such as SeaWorld have not collected wild orcas in over 35 years.\n\n27 of the 34 orcas on display in the US, Canada, Argentina, Spain, and France were born in captivity. 6 of the 7 displayed in Japan are captive-born. An additional 13 orcas reported in China and Russia were captured in Russian waters.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nKalina, born in September 1985, was the first captive-born orca calf to survive more than a few days. In September 2001, [[Kasatka]] gave birth to Nakai, the first orca conceived through [[artificial insemination]], at [[SeaWorld San Diego]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1523214.stm \"Artificially inseminated killer whale gives birth\"] BBC. Retrieved (sad) February 14, 2009.</ref> This technique lets park owners maintain a more healthy genetic mix in the small groups of orcas at each park, while avoiding the stress of moving orcas for breeding purposes.<ref>[http://nationalzoo.si.edu/ConservationAndScience/SpotlightOnScience/monfortorca20040618.cfm \"Artificial Insemination Produces Killer Whales\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204120553/http://nationalzoo.si.edu/ConservationAndScience/SpotlightOnScience/monfortorca20040618.cfm |date=February 4, 2009 }} Smithsonian National Zoological Park. Retrieved February 14, 2009.</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! sco\n!Age\n|-\n| [[#Ad\u00e1n|Ad\u00e1n]] || M \n|87.5% Icelandic \u2013 12.5% Southern residents|| alive || [[Loro Parque]] \n|Captive born||13 October 2010\n|9\n|-\n|Alexandra\n|F\n|100% Russian\n|alive\n|Center for Adaptation of Marine Mammals\n|Captured\n|2017 (est.) \u2013 August 2018 \u2013 16 July 2019\n|2\n|- \n| [[List of captive orcas#Amaya|Amaya]]|| F\n|93.75% Icelandic \u2013 6.25% Southern Residents|| alive||[[SeaWorld San Diego]]\n|Captive born||2 December 2014\n|5\n|-\n| [[#Corky|Corky II]]|| F\n|100% Northern Residents|| alive ||[[SeaWorld San Diego]]\n|Captured|| 1965 (est.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.whales.org/wdc-in-action/free-corky|title=Corky's Story|publisher=}}</ref> \u2013 12 December 1969\n|55\n|-\n|[[#Earth|Earth]]|| M\n|100% Icelandic|| alive ||[[Port of Nagoya Public Aquarium|Port of Nagoya Aquarium]]\n|Captive born||13 October 2008\n|11\n|-\n|Dora\n|F\n|100% Russian Transient\n|alive\n|Shanghai Haichang Ocean Park\n|Captured\n|2012 (est.) \u2013 2015 (unconfirmed)\n|7\n|-\n|Forest\n|Unknown\n|100% Russian\n|alive\n|Center for Adaptation of Marine Mammals\n|Captured\n|Unknown \u2013 August 2018\n|3\n|-\n|Gaika\n|F\n|100% Russian\n|alive\n|Center for Adaptation of Marine Mammals\n|Captured\n|Unknown \u2013 August 2018\n|3\n|-\n|Grace\n|F\n|100% Russian Tranisent\n|alive\n|Chimelong Ocean Kingdom\n|Captured\n|2010 (est.) \u2013 13 August 2013\n|8\n|-\n|Harja\n|Unknown\n|100% Russian\n|alive\n|Center for Adaptation of Marine Mammals\n|Captured\n|Unknown \u2013 August 2018\n|5\n|-\n| [[#Ikaika|Ikaika]]|| M\n|100% Icelandic|| alive || [[SeaWorld San Diego]]\n|Captive born||25 August 2002\n|17\n|-\n| [[List of captive orcas#Inouk|Inouk]]|| M\n|100% Icelandic|| alive ||[[Marineland of Antibes]]\n|Captive born||23 February 1999\n|21\n|-\n| [[#Kalia|Kalia]]|| F\n|87.5% Icelandic \u2013 12.5% Southern Residents|| alive || [[SeaWorld San Diego]]\n|Captive born||21 December 2004\n|15\n|-\n| [[List of captive orcas#Kamea|Kamea]]|| F\n|50% Argentinian Transient \u2013 50% Icelandic|| alive || [[SeaWorld San Antonio]]\n|Captive born||{{Birth date and age|df=yes|2013|12|06}}\n|5\n|-\n| [[#Katina|Katina]] (Kandu 6)|| F\n|100% Icelandic|| alive ||[[SeaWorld Orlando]]\n|Captured|| 1975 (est.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shamudictionary.tumblr.com/post/15131509854/orca-profile-katina|title=Shamu Dictionary!|website=Shamu Dictionary!}}</ref>\n|45\n|-\n| [[#Keet|Keet]]|| M\n|75% Icelandic \u2013 25% Southern Residents|| alive || [[SeaWorld San Diego]]\n|Captive born||{{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|02|02}}\n|27\n|-\n|[[#Keijo|Keijo]]|| M\n|100% Icelandic|| alive ||[[Mari